#. <section class="sutta" id="an3.113"><article><div class="hgroup"><p class="division">
msgctxt "an3.113:0.1"
msgid "Aṅguttara Nikāya 3"
msgstr "Numbered Discourses 3"

#. </p><p>
msgctxt "an3.113:0.2"
msgid "12. Āpāyikavagga"
msgstr "12. Bound for Loss"

#. </p><h1>
msgctxt "an3.113:0.3"
msgid "113. Āpāyikasutta"
msgstr "113. Bound for Loss"

#. </h1></div><p>
#. <a class="pts-vp-pi" id="pts-vp-pi1.266"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc1"></a>
msgctxt "an3.113:1.1"
msgid "“Tayome, bhikkhave, āpāyikā nerayikā idamappahāya."
msgstr ""
"“Mendicants, three kinds of people are bound for a place of loss, bound for "
"hell, if they don’t give up this fault."

msgctxt "an3.113:1.2"
msgid "Katame tayo?"
msgstr "What three?"

# BB in his note on this notes that comm connects pātabyata in this idiom to pivati. However in the parallel to DN 27 at Mu Kd 17, we have pātakavratam āpannās which must derive from pāta= fall.
msgctxt "an3.113:1.3"
msgid "Yo ca abrahmacārī brahmacāripaṭiñño, "
msgstr "Someone who is unchaste, but claims to be celibate;"

#. VAR: amūlakena → abhūtena (mr)
msgctxt "an3.113:1.4"
msgid ""
"yo ca suddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carantaṃ amūlakena abrahmacariyena anuddhaṃseti, "
msgstr ""
"someone who makes a groundless accusation of unchastity against a person "
"whose celibacy is pure; "

msgctxt "an3.113:1.5"
msgid ""
"yo cāyaṃ evaṃvādī evaṃdiṭṭhi: ‘natthi kāmesu doso’ti, so tāya kāmesu "
"pātabyataṃ āpajjati."
msgstr ""
"someone who has the view, ‘There is nothing wrong with sensual pleasures,’ "
"so they throw themselves into sensual pleasures."

msgctxt "an3.113:1.6"
msgid "Ime kho, bhikkhave, tayo āpāyikā nerayikā idamappahāyā”ti."
msgstr ""
"These are the three kinds of people bound for a place of loss, bound for "
"hell, if they don’t give up this fault.”"

#. </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "an3.113:1.7"
msgid "Paṭhamaṃ."
msgstr ""
